A number of indices are referenced above. Any comparison of the Funds' retumsto these indices inherent limitations. The portfolio composition of the
Funds and the indices differ, as do their investment chara cteristics. Comparing the returns of these indices to the Funds' returns may be of limited use. The
S&P 500 index is a broad based measurement of changes in stock market conditions based on the average performance of 500 widely held stocks including
industrial, transportation, financial, and utility stocks. The MSCI Index is a market-capitalization weighted index that is designed to measure the equity market
performance of developed markets. The MSCIndex onsists of 23 developed market country indices and 21 emerging market indices. The index is based
on the MSCIGlobal Investable Market Indices (GIMI) Methodology-an approach to index construction that is intended to allow for meaningful global views
and cross regional comparisons across all market capitalization size, sector and style segments and combinations. The index is reviewed quarterly and
rebalanced semi-annually. The Russell 2000 Index measures the performance of the 2,000 smallest companies in the Russell 3000 Index, which is made up of
3,000 of the largest U.S. stocks by marketc apitalization. The Russell 2000 Index represents approximately 8% of the total market capitalization of the Russell
3000 Index. The HFRX EH: Equity Market Neutral Index is comprised of market neutral strategies, which employ sophisticated quantitative techniques of
analyzing price data to ertain informationabout future price movement and relationships between securities, select securities for purchase and sale.
These can include both factor-based and statistical arbitrage/trading strategies. The HFRX Equity Hedge Index is comprised of equity hedge strategies
maintain positions both long short in primarily equity and equity derivative securities. A wide variety of investment processes may be employed,
including both quantitative and funda menta techniques; strategies may be broadly diversified or narrowly foc used on specific sectors and can range
broadly in terms of levels net exposure, leverage, concentration and valuation ranges. The HFRX Global Hedge Index is comprised of eight strategies:
convertible arbitrage, mergerarbitrage, equity hedge, equity market neutral, relative value arbitrage, event driven, distressed securities, and macro. The
strategies are asset weighted based on the distribution of assets in the hedge fund industry. The HFR Indices are calculated by Hedge Fund Research based
on information that is voluntarily provided. As a result, ctual returns may be higher or lower than those reported.
